=== [ topic ][ class and id ][ double quote ] ===
[ --- start ---- ]
Question: Are quotes required around HTML 5 attributes?
Answer:
When writing HTML 5 attributes, you do not need to use quotation marks to
define the value. When you don't use quotation marks you cannot use the
following characters in your attribute values:

double and single quote marks (" and ')
spaces ( )
equal sign (=)
greater-than sign (>)

Incorrect HTML 5 attributes:
<p class=blah blah>
<p class=blah=blah>
<p class=blah>blah>
<p class=blah'blah>
<p class=blah"blah>

Correct HTML 5 attributes:
<p class=blahblah>
<p class="blah blah">
<p class=blah&#61;blah>
<p class=blah&gt;blah>
<p class="blah'blah">
<p class='blah"blah'>
